College student Riya put up an online ad to sell her old phone. A few hours later, she got a message from a "buyer" who expressed interest and agreed to make an instant UPI payment. She received a QR code from the buyer, who told her to scan it in order to "receive" the money. Riya scanned the code and input her UPI PIN, following the directions. Rather than getting paid, her account was debited ₹10,000.
The following steps are usually involved in this kind of fraud.
Pretending to be a buyer or customer, the con artist contacts the victim.
They foster trust and create a sense of urgency (e.g., quick payment offer).
They send a payment request or a QR code.
The victim is tricked into inputting their UPI PIN.
The con artist acquires money right away.
Due to their frequent use of digital platforms and potential ignorance of UPI security procedures, college students and online vendors are frequently targeted.
Financial loss, psychological strain, and a decline in confidence in online systems are among the repercussions. since digital transactions are often immediate and irreversible, victims may also find it difficult to get their money back.
